        "title": "USS Nausett (1865)",
        "content": "{{other ships|USS Nausett}}\n{{One source|date=November 2021}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:USS Nausett 1865.jpg|300px|Engraving of USS Nausett]]\n|Ship caption=An engraving of the USS ''Nausett'' published in the English magazine \"Engineering\", 13 July 1866.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1875}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Nausett''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=April 1863\n|Ship builder=[[Donald McKay]], Boston, Massachusetts\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=26 April 1865\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=10 August 1865\n|Ship decommissioned=24 August 1865\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Broken up, August 1875\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass|Casco|monitor||warship}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|1175|LT|t|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|225|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|45|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|9|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=Screw steamer\n|Ship speed={{convert|9|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=69 officers and enlisted\n|Ship armament=2 × {{convert|11|in|mm|abbr=on}} smoothbore [[Dahlgren gun]]s\n|Ship armor=*'''[[Gun turret|Turret]]:''' {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n*'''[[Pilothouse]]:''' {{convert|10|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n*'''Hull:''' {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n*'''[[Deck (ship)|Deck]]:''' {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Nausett''''', a [[gun turret|single-turreted]], [[Propeller (marine)|twin-screw]] [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]], was built by [[Donald McKay]], [[South Boston, MA]], and launched on 26 April 1865, and commissioned on 10 August 1865, [[Brevet (military)|Acting]] [[Master (naval)|Master]] Win. U. Grozier in command. Soon after her commissioning, she steamed to [[New York, NY]], where she decommissioned on 24 August 1865, and was laid up at the [[New York Navy Yard]].\n\n''Nausett'' was a ''Casco''-class, light-draft monitor intended for service in the shallow bays, rivers, and inlets of the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]]. These warships sacrificed [[armor plate]] for a shallow [[draft (hull)|draft]] and were fitted with a [[Sailing ballast|ballast]] compartment designed to lower them in the water during battle.\n\n==Design revisions==\n{{stack|[[File:FMIB 37114 Le Monitor Americain Le Nauset, construit a Boston en 1862.jpg|thumb|Model of the ''Nausett'', built in Boston in 1862]]}}\nThe contract to Donald McKay was originally announced in 1863.<ref>{{cite news|title=Donald McKay to Build an Iron-Clad|url=http://digital.tcl.sc.edu/cdm/ref/collection/NSN/id/432|access-date=1 October 2014|work=The New South|date=14 November 1863}}</ref>  Though the original designs for the ''Casco''-class monitors were drawn by [[John Ericsson]], the final revision was created by Chief Engineer Alban C. Stimers following [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Samuel F. Du Pont]]'s failed bombardment of [[Fort Sumter]] in 1863. By the time that the plans were put before the Monitor Board in [[New York City]], Ericsson and Stimers had a poor relationship, and Chief of the [[Bureau of Construction and Repair]] [[John Lenthall (shipbuilder)|John Lenthall]] had little connection to the board. This resulted in the plans being approved and 20 vessels ordered without serious scrutiny of the new design. $14 million US was allocated for the construction of these vessels. It was discovered that Stimers had failed to compensate for the armor his revisions added to the original plan and this resulted in excessive stress on the wooden hull frames and a freeboard of only {{convert|3|in|cm|abbr=on}}. Stimers was removed from the control of the project and Ericsson was called in to undo the damage. He was forced to raise the hulls of the monitors under construction by {{convert|22|in|cm|abbr=on}} to make them seaworthy.\n\n==Fate==\nAs a result, ''Nausett'' remained in ordinary at New York for 10 years, during which time she was renamed twice: '''''Aetna''''' on 15 June 1869; and back to ''Nausett'' on 10 August 1869. In August 1875, she was broken up by John Roach of New York.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/n2/nausett-i.htm}}\n\n{{Casco class light draft monitor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nausett (1865)}}\n[[Category:Casco-class monitors]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Boston]]\n[[Category:1865 ships]]"
