        "title": "Wincenty Rzymowski",
        "content": "{{short description|Polish politician and writer}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image               = Wincenty Rzymowski pocztówka (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize           = 185px\n| caption             = \n| office              = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Poland)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister       = \n| predecessor         = [[Edward Osóbka-Morawski]]\n| successor           = [[Zygmunt Modzelewski]]\n| term_start          = June 1945\n| term_end            = 6 February 1947\n| office1             = [[Ministry of Culture and National Heritage (Poland)|Minister of Culture]]\n| primeminister1      = \n| predecessor1        = [[Zygmunt Kaczyński]]\n| successor1          = [[Edmund Zalewski]]\n| term_start1         = 21 June 1944\n| term_end1           = 2 May 1945\n| office2             = \n| primeminister2      = \n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| term_start2         = \n| term_end2           = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1883|6|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kuczbork-Osada]], [[Congress Poland]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1950|4|30|1883|6|19|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Warsaw]], [[Polish People's Republic]]\n| restingplace        = \n| party               = [[Polish United Workers' Party]]\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Odesa University]]\n| spouse              = \n| nationality         = [[Polish people|Polish]]\n| children            = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| profession          = Politician, diplomat, writer\n| awards              = [[Order of the Banner of Labour]] <br> [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] <br> [[Medal for Warsaw 1939–1945]]<br>[[Medal of Victory and Freedom 1945]]<br>[[Order of the Star of the Romanian Socialist Republic]]<br>[[Order of Stara Planina]]\n| name                = \n}}\n\n'''Wincenty Rzymowski''' (19 July 1883, in [[Kuczbork-Osada]] – 30 April 1950, in [[Warsaw]]) was a Polish politician and writer. Rzymowski was one of the many [[History of Poland (1945–1989)#Stalinist era (1948–1956)|faces of Stalinism]] in [[People's Republic of Poland|postwar Poland]].\n\n==Career ==\nIn the [[Second Polish Republic]], Wincenty Rzymowski was a member of the [[Democratic Party (Poland)|Democratic Party]] and a known [[publicist]]. He was also forced to resign his membership in the [[Polish Academy of Literature]] in a controversy involving allegations of [[plagiarism]].<ref name=\"ipn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal/pl/398/4916/ | title=Wincenty Rzymowski (1883–1950) | publisher=[[Instytut Pamięci Narodowej]] | date=2011 | access-date=December 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]] he began collaborating with the [[Soviet Union|Soviets]]. He joined the [[Union of Polish Patriots]], was a Minister of Arts and Culture in the [[Polish Committee of National Liberation]] and a Minister of Foreign Affairs in the [[Provisional Government of National Unity]], formed by [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]. He represented Poland during the signing of the [[United Nations Charter]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.trumanlibrary.gov/photograph-records/99-1027 |title=Wincenty Rzymowski of the Polish Provisional Government of National Unity Signing the United Nations Charter |publisher=Harry S. Truman Presidential Library and Museum |access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref> In January 1946, he was a [[Soviet Union and the United Nations|Soviet]] candidate for the position of the first [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General of the United Nations]], but opposed by the [[United States and the United Nations|United States]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Hamilton |first=Thomas J. |date=1950 |title=The U. N. and Trygve Lie |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/20030815 |journal=Foreign Affairs |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=69 |doi=10.2307/20030815 |jstor=20030815 |issn=0015-7120}}</ref> The two powers eventually compromised on [[Trygve Lie]], a socialist from Norway.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWincenty Rzymowski was also a deputy to the [[State National Council]] and [[Legislative Sejm (1947-1952)|Legislative Sejm]]. From 1947 till the end of his life he was a [[minister without portfolio]] in the Polish communist government.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Wincenty Rzymowski}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Poland|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rzymowski, Wincenty}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Żuromin County]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Democrats (Poland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of foreign affairs of Poland]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Members of the State National Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 1947–1952]]\n[[Category:Diplomats of the Polish People's Republic]]\n[[Category:Controversies in Poland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Academy of Literature]]\n[[Category:Commanders with Star of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Banner of Work]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Cross of Merit (Poland)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Powązki Cemetery]]\n\n\n{{Poland-politician-stub}}"
