        "title": "Louise Clapp",
        "content": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{about|the baseball player|the tennis player|Louise Brough Clapp}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name=Louise Clapp\n| image=\n| image_size=\n| team=[[All-American Girls Professional Baseball League]] \n| position=[[Pitcher]]\n| birth_date={{birth_date|1934|05|12|mf=y}}<ref name=Ancestry.com>{{cite web |url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gl=ROOT_CATEGORY&rank=1&new=1&so=3&MSAV=0&msT=1&gss=ms_f-2_s&gsfn=Louise&gsln=Clapp&mswpn__ftp=Harrod%2C+Allen%2C+Ohio%2C+USA&mswpn=50480&mswpn_PInfo=8-%7C0%7C1652393%7C0%7C2%7C3247%7C38%7C0%7C150%7C50480%7C0%7C&msbdy=1936&uidh=000 |title= Ancestry.com – Search for Louise Lucelia Clapp: b. 12 May 1934 (Harrod, Allen County, Ohio); d. 17 October 1967 (Cleveland, Cuyahoga County, Ohio)}}</ref>\n| birth_place=[[Harrod, Ohio]]<ref name=Ancestry.com/>\n| death_date={{death_date and age|1967|10|17|1934|05|12}}<ref name=Ancestry.com/> \n| death_place=[[Cleveland, Ohio]]<ref name=Ancestry.com/>\n| bats=Right\n| throws=Right\n| teams =\n*[[Fort Wayne Daisies]] (1954)\n*[[South Bend Blue Sox]] (1954)\n|highlights=\n*Women in Baseball – AAGPBL Permanent Display<br>at Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum (1988)\n}}\n\n'''Louise Lucelia Clapp''' (May 12, 1934 – October 17, 1967) was a [[pitcher]] who played in the [[All-American Girls Professional Baseball League]]. She batted and threw right-handed.<ref name=AAGPBL>{{cite web |url=http://www.aagpbl.org/profiles/louise-clapp/255|title=All-American Girls Professional Baseball League – Louise Clapp|accessdate=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n\nLittle is known about this player who saw action in the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League during the [[1954 All-American Girls Professional Baseball League season|1954 season]].\n\nClapp split the year between the [[Fort Wayne Daisies]] and [[South Bend Blue Sox]] teams. She hurled five [[innings pitched|innings]] of ball in three pitching appearances.<ref name=AAGPBL/>\n\nThe league folded at the end of the season. Clapp was not located after that.<ref name=AAGPBL/>\n\nShe is part of ''Women in Baseball'', a permanent display based at the [[Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] in [[Cooperstown, New York]], which was unveiled in 1988 to honor the entire All-American Girls Professional Baseball League.\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}} \n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clapp, Louise}}\n[[Category:All-American Girls Professional Baseball League players]]\n[[Category:Fort Wayne Daisies players]]\n[[Category:South Bend Blue Sox players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:People from Harrod, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American sportswomen]]"
