        "title": "Thomas Cooper (Parliamentarian)",
        "content": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Thomas Cooper''' (died 1659) was a colonel in the Parliamentary Army who fought in the [[English Civil War]] and aided in the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Cromwellian occupation of Ireland]]. He was appointed to the [[Cromwell's Upper House]], and died in 1659.<ref name=Noble-426>Noble, [https://books.google.com/books?id=SFkUAAAAQAAJ&dq=%22Noble%20Memoirs%20of%20the%20Protectoral%20Family%22&pg=PA426 p. 426]</ref><ref>Reid [https://books.google.com/books?id=5fwQAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=RA1-PA299 p. 299 footnote (12)][sic] (should be 21) \"Accordingly Thomas Cooper was recalled from Scotland and appointed commander in Ulster, ... . He arrived in Dublin in the beginning of January 1656,  and reached [[Carrickfergus]] in the first week of February. He resided here till January, 1658, when he retired to London where he died in the latter end of the year 1659. Thurloe, iii 744 and iv. 408 552, vi 734. Com. Journ. vii 804.\"</ref>\n\nCooper was of an ancient and respectable family in [[Oxfordshire]], which had possessed the manor of [[South Weston]], with other estates in that county for several centuries; he was an alderman of Oxford, which place he represented in the [[Short Parliament]] called by King [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] in 1640, with Lord Howard; but that assembly, having been most imprudently dissolved,<ref group=nb>Nobel could have misread his source, this may have been another Thomas Cooper (c.1593–1640) who was Mayor of Oxford in 1628 (Jenkins, Stephanie. [http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/mayors/1603_1714/cooper_thomas_1630.html Thomas Cooper Mayor of Oxford 1630/1], website of [http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/mayors/contact/index.html Oxford History, Oxford] Retrieved 3 August 2012)</ref> he was again returned to the [[Long Parliament]]. He rose in the Parliament army to the rank of Colonel of foot, and accompanied Oliver Cromwell into Scotland in 1651. He afterwards was sent into Ireland. In 1656, he was one of the representatives of the counties of Down, Antrim, and Armagh, in the latter kingdom. Some time after the initial nominations, he accepted the nomination as a lord in [[Cromwell's Upper House]]. His name is under the order for proclaiming [[Richard Cromwell]] Protector. What he may have gained during the usurpation was not known to Mark Nobel, who was writing at the end of the eighteenth century,  but Nobel speculated that perhaps it was considerable; for though Cooper was a great sufferer by the [[English Restoration|restoration of the monarchy]], his descendant and heir, Thomas Cooper, Esq. inhered the manor at South Weston, with other properties, in Oxfordshire, of the value of £1000 per annum.<ref name=Noble-426/><ref group=nb>Noble is supported by Reid, basing his account on [[John Thurloe]]'s manuscripts as a source, assert that the Thomas Cooper who was an English soldier who moved from Scotland to Ireland, was the Thomas Cooper who was also in London in 1658. Noble is also supported by Anne Conway, who in a footnote to a letter dated 5 July 1659 to from<!--to? from?--> [[Edward Conway, 1st Earl of Conway|Lord Conway]] in [[Kensington]], to his brother Major Rawdon. In it Conway states he had recently spoken to a Colonel Cooper (presumably in London) to which Conway states in a footnote \"Thomas Cooper whom Cromwell had put in charge of forces in Ulster in 1655\".(Conway [https://books.google.com/books?id=V6nSSa8GQ7sC&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=PA160 p. 160 footnote]).\n\nHowever Aidan Clarke states that the Colonel Thomas Cooper who was in Ulster was a Scotsman and that he died in Ulster on 21 December 1659.(Clarke [https://books.google.com/books?id=m6EeHCUYJGwC&q=Thomas+Cooper&pg=PA58 pp. 58, 115])</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n;Citations\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Clarke, Aidan (1999). ''Prelude to restoration in Ireland: the end of the Commonwealth, 1659-1660'', Cambridge University Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-521-65061-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-521-65061-8}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=m6EeHCUYJGwC&q=Thomas+Cooper&pg=PA115 p.324 Index] \"Cooper Col. Thomas 33, 58, 60, 62, 69, 94n, 97, 98, 99, 100,1 03, 114-115, 119, 143, 151, 172, 264n\"\n*Conway Anne, ''et al.''(1992). ''The Conway letters: the correspondence of Anne, Viscountess Conway, Henry More, and their friends, 1642-1684'', Oxford University Press, 1992. [https://books.google.com/books?id=V6nSSa8GQ7sC&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=PA160 p. 160 footnote].\n*[[Mark Noble (biographer)|Noble, Mark]] (1784). ''Memoirs of the protectorate-house of Cromwell: deduced from an early period, and continued down to the present time'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=qFQDAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA387 Volume II], Printed Pearson and Rollason, sold by R. Baldwin [etc.] London.\n*Reid, James Seaton (1838).  ''History of the Presbyterian Church in Ireland: comprising the civil history of the province of Ulster, from the accession of James the First, with a preliminary sketch of the progress of the reformed religion in Ireland during the sixteenth century and an appendix consisting of original papers'', Volume 2, Whittaker. [https://books.google.com/books?id=5fwQAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=RA1-PA299 p. 299 footnote (12)]\n\n;Attribution\n* {{source-attribution|\"Memoirs of the protectorate-house of Cromwell: deduced from an early period, and continued down to the present time\" by Mark Noble (1784)}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Editors. ''The Gentleman's magazine'', Volume 191 ''Gleanings from the Irish Council Books'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=Tf4RAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=PA351 p. 1852] Letter from Henry Cromwell to Cooper and others in charge in Ulster over religion\n*Notes and queries, Volume 11, January–June 1867.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=67QRAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Thomas+Cooper%22Cromwell&pg=RA1-PA417 p. 417] [https://books.google.com/books?id=67QRAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA491 pp. 491,492] \"Thomas Cooper (3rd S. xi 417.) E. H. C is referred to a statement in Burke's ''Armory'', from whence it appears that Thomas Cooper, Colonel in Cromwell's army, called to the Protector's Upper House in 1658, is now represented by the family of Thomas Beale Cooper, M.D., of Mansion House, Bengeworth, Esq., whose pedigree may probably be found in that author's ''Landed Gentry''. — ; Pingatoris.\"\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coper, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1659 deaths]]\n[[Category:Roundheads]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640 (April)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640–1648]]\n[[Category:Members of Cromwell's Other House]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]"
