        "content": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name=10.5 cm howitzer Model 1924\n|image=COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Militaire optocht in Batavia TMnr 60030917 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size=300\n|caption=A military parade in Jakarta.\n|origin=Sweden\n|type=[[Howitzer]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=\n|is_bladed=\n|is_explosive=\n|is_artillery=yes\n|is_vehicle=\n|is_UK=\n<!-- Service history -->\n|service=1924–1945\n|used_by={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|wars=[[World War II]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=[[Bofors]]\n|design_date= \n|manufacturer=[[Bofors]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Light and medium field artillery|last=Chamberlain|first=Peter|date=1975|page=45|publisher=Arco|others=Gander, Terry|isbn=0668038209|location=New York|oclc=2067331}}</ref>\n|production_date=\n|number=\n|variants=\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight={{convert|1,650|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|length=\n|part_length={{convert|2.31|m|ftin|abbr=on}} L/22<ref name=\":0\" />\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications --> \n|cartridge={{convert|14|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|caliber=105 mm (4.134 in)\n|action=\n|rate=\n|velocity=475 m/s (1,560 ft/s)\n|range=\n|max_range={{convert|10.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n|feed=\n|sights=\n<!-- Artillery specifications -->\n|breech=\n|recoil=\n|carriage=[[Gun carriage#Modern gun carriages|box trail]]\n|elevation=-5° to +45°\n|traverse=360°<ref name=\":0\" />\n<!-- Bladed weapon specifications --> \n|blade_type=\n|hilt_type=\n|sheath_type=\n|head_type=\n|haft_type=\n<!-- Explosive specifications --> \n|diameter=\n|filling=\n|filling_weight=\n|detonation=\n|yield=\n<!-- Vehicle specifications -->\n|armour=\n|primary_armament=\n|secondary_armament=\n|engine=\n|engine_power=\n|pw_ratio=\n|suspension=\n|vehicle_range=\n|speed=\n}}\nThe '''10.5&nbsp;cm howitzer Model 1924''' was a howitzer used by the Netherlands during [[World War II]]. Fourteen were bought by the [[KNIL|Royal Dutch East Indies Army]], where they equipped the 1st Howitzer Artillery Battalion, from 1924 to 1945. It is unknown if the Japanese used them after conquering the [[Dutch East Indies campaign|Dutch East Indies]] in 1942.\n\nThis weapon was designed for motor traction with rubber-rimmed steel wheels. Maximum towing speed was only 30&nbsp;km/h (18.6&nbsp;mph). It had a firing platform that gave it 360° traverse. On mount traverse was only 8° 30'.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* Chamberlain, Peter & Gander, Terry. ''Light and Medium Field Artillery''. New York: Arco, 1975\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080821102913/http://www.overvalwagen.com/KNILartillery.html Artillery of the K.N.I.L. on Overvalwagens!]\n\n{{Weapons made in Sweden 1914–1945|style=wide}}\n\n[[Category:World War II field artillery]]\n[[Category:105 mm artillery]]\n\n\n{{artillery-stub}}"
