        "title": "Black Orchids (film)",
        "content": "{{short description|1917 film by Rex Ingram}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Black Orchids\n| image          = Black Orchids.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Film poster\n| native_name      = \n| director       = [[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Rex Ingram\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based_on       = \n| starring       = {{plainlist|*[[Cleo Madison]]\n*[[Francis McDonald]]\n*[[Dick La Reno]]}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Duke Hayward]]\n| editing        = \n| studio         = Bluebird Photoplays\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Film Manufacturing Company]]\n| released       = {{film date|1917|1|1|ref1=<ref name=AFI/>}}\n| runtime        = 5 reels\n| country        = United States\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Black Orchids''''' is a 1917 American [[Silent film|silent drama film]] written and directed by [[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]]. The film was released as ''The Fatal Orchids'' in the [[United Kingdom]]. The feature stars [[Cleo Madison]], [[Francis McDonald]] and [[Dick La Reno]]. Ingram later remade the film as ''[[Trifling Women]]'' (1922).\n\n''Black Orchids'' is considered a [[lost film]].<ref name=PSFL/><ref name=LOC/>\n\n==Plot==\nThe synopsis released by the studio as printed in ''Motography'' reads:<ref name=Motog1702/>\n\n{{Blockquote|text=The story is told as one a novelist relates to his daughter to warn her against waywardness. Zoraida, a fortune-teller, has many admirers, among them a diplomat and his son, Ivan. The father sends the son away. Later the woman falls in love with his best friend, the marquis. The diplomat plans to poison the marquis but falls into his own trap and dies. Zoraida marries the marquis. Ivan returns from the war, quarrels with the marquis and fights a duel with him. He wounds him fatally but before his death the marquis plans a revenge which brings about the death of Zoraida and Ivan.}}\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Cleo Madison]] as Marie de Severac/Zoraida\n*[[Francis McDonald]] as George Renoir/Ivan\n*[[Dick La Reno]] as Emile de Severac\n*[[Wedgwood Nowell]] as Marquis de Chantal\n*[[Howard Crampton]] as Baron de Maupin\n*[[John George (actor)|John George]] as Ali Bara\n*[[William Dyer (actor)|William J. Dyer]] as Proprietor of l'Hirbour Blanc\n\n==Reviews and reception==\nA write-up about the film in the ''Exhibitor's Trade Review'' notes that the story-telling device served to sidestep the censors: \"Indeed, were it not for this method of picturing the adventures of the man-enslaving Zoraida, one can hardly imagine the film being offered as screen entertainment, in this country at least.\"<ref name=soister/> Edward Weitzel wrote in his review of the film in the ''Moving Picture World'', that the drama \"deals almost exclusively with open defiance of all moral law, but&nbsp;... holds the spectator's undivided attention to the end\". Weitzel also commented on Ingram's direction, saying: \"While no points of the plot are glossed over or left in doubt, there is no undue stress put upon any of the incidents and the atmosphere which surrounds the entire story belongs to it by right of birth.\"<ref name=MPW3101/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=AFI>{{cite web |title=Black Orchids |work=Catalog of Feature Films |publisher=American Film Institute |url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=14471 |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref>\n<ref name=PSFL>{{cite web |editor=Carl Bennett |title=Black Orchids |work=Progressive Silent Film List |date=January 13, 2004 |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/BlackOrchids1917.html |accessdate=2015-10-21 |via=Silent Era}}</ref>\n<ref name=LOC>{{cite web |author=David Pierce |title=Black Orchids/Rex Ingram |work=American Silent Feature Film Survival Database |publisher=Library of Congress |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov:8081/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.3790/default.html |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref>\n<ref name=soister>{{cite book |author=John T. Soister |title=American Silent Horror, Science Fiction and Fantasy Feature Films, 1913–1929 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajXwxJuYd5gC&pg=PA46 |year=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-8790-5 |pages=46–47}}</ref>\n<ref name=MPW3101>{{cite journal |title=Black Orchids |author=Edward Weitzel |journal=Moving Picture World |date=January 6, 1917 |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=98–99 |url=https://archive.org/stream/movwor31chal#page/98/mode/1up |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref>\n<ref name=Motog1702>{{cite journal |title=Black Orchids |journal=Motography |date=January 13, 1917 |volume=XVII |issue=2 |page=107 |url=https://archive.org/stream/motography17elec#page/107/mode/1up |accessdate=2015-10-21}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0006434|title=Black Orchids}}\n*{{Tcmdb title|id=489328|title=Black Orchids}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150419233214/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/85226/Black-Orchids/overview ''Black Orchids'' (1917)] at ''New York Times'' Movies\n\n{{Rex Ingram}}\n\n[[Category:1917 films]]\n[[Category:1917 drama films]]\n[[Category:Silent American drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Rex Ingram]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Lost American drama films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:1917 lost films]]\n[[Category:1910s American films]]"
