        "title": "Sokołów Małopolski",
        "content": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Sokołów Małopolski\n| image_skyline = Sokołów Małopolski (ul. Rynek) - magistrat.jpg\n| image_caption = Town hall\n| image_shield = POL Sokołów Małopolski COA.svg\n| pushpin_map = Poland\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| subdivision_type = [[list of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Podkarpackie Voivodeship|name=Subcarpathian}}\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of Polish counties|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Rzeszów County|Rzeszów]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Gmina]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Gmina Sokołów Małopolski|Sokołów Małopolski]]\n| established_title = Town rights\n| established_date = 1569\n| leader_party = [[Law and Justice|PiS]]\n| leader_title = Mayor\n| leader_name = Andrzej Kraska\n| area_total_km2 = 15.55\n| population_as_of = 2005\n| population_total = 4046\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| timezone = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| coordinates = {{coord|50|13|57|N|22|7|15|E|region:PL|display=title,inline}}\n| postal_code_type = Postal code\n| postal_code = 36-050\n| registration_plate = RZE\n| blank_name_sec2 = Primary airport\n| blank_info_sec2 = [[Rzeszów–Jasionka Airport]]\n| blank1_name_sec2 = [[Highways in Poland|Highway]]\n| blank1_info_sec2 = [[File:S19-PL.svg|32px|link=Expressway S19 (Poland)]]\n| website = http://www.sokolow-mlp.pl\n}}\n'''Sokołów Małopolski''' {{IPAc-pl|s|o|'|k|o|ł|u|f|-|m|a|ł|o|'|p|o|l|s|k|J|i}} is a town in [[Rzeszów County]], [[Subcarpathian Voivodeship]], [[Poland]], with a population of 3,962 <small>(2 June 2009).</small><ref name=\"GUS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.gov.pl/cps/rde/xbcr/gus/PUBL_P_population_size_structure_31_12_2008.pdf|title=Population. Size and structure by territorial division|last=|first=|date=2009-06-02|website=|publisher=Central Statistical Office|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSokołów Małopolski lies in [[Sandomierz Basin]], 24 kilometers north of Rzeszow, and 11 kilometers from [[Rzeszów–Jasionka Airport]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sokołów Małopolski (kościół św. Jana Chrzciciela).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Saint John church]]\n[[File:Sokolowa Malopolski 1905-1918 (71359344) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Market square, ca 1905-1918]]\nThe history of Sokołów Małopolski starts with a forest settlement, located in once extensive [[Sandomierz Forest]], which the sources describe as far as the 14th century. In 1569, Sokołów received a town charter, with a Renaissance street plan and a market square in the centre. In 1608, the town was looted by [[Stanislaw Stadnicki]], a well-known troublemaker and the so-called “Devil of [[Łańcut]]”, but after this incident, Sokolow continued to prosper. In 1657, during the [[Deluge (history)|Swedish invasion of Poland]], Sokolow was destroyed by [[Transilvania]]n army of [[George II Rakoczi]].\n\nFollowing the [[First Partition of Poland]], Sokołów was in 1772 annexed by the [[Habsburg monarchy|Habsburg Empire]], and remained in Austrian [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] until late 1918. The town burned in fires in 1863 and 1904, and did not prosper. In the [[Second Polish Republic]], Sokolow belonged to [[Lwow Voivodeship]], and even though it was located in the [[Central Industrial Region (Poland)|Central Industrial Region]], no plant was opened here, and the promised rail line was not built.\n\nIn the 17th century, the town was protected by fortifications with five gates and moat. Sokolow has a 17th-century Jewish cemetery, and a parish church (1908–1916). Today, due to numerous wars and fires, there are only buildings from the 19th and 20th centuries. In 2010, local villagers helped to clean up the Jewish cemetery, though without the cooperation of local officials who reportedly said they didn't want to cooperate with Jews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polish Villagers Clean Up Jewish Cemetery |url=https://www.jpost.com/jewish-world/jewish-news/polish-villagers-clean-up-jewish-cemetery |publisher=Jerusalem Post |accessdate=July 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the German [[invasion of Poland]] in September, 1939, Sokołów Małopolski's Jewish population was about 1,600. The Germans immediately requisitioned Jews for [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|forced labor]]. In April 1942, the Jewish population, then numbering 3,000 because of refugees and others resettled by the Germans in Sokołów Małopolski, was forced into a [[Jewish ghettos established by Nazi Germany|ghetto]]. In July, German police shot 30 residents of the ghetto, resettled 200 in a labor camp in Głogów, and moved others to the Rzeszów ghetto where they were sent to the [[Belzec extermination camp]] in July. Several dozens of Jews who hid from the deportations were murdered later in the year and in the summer of 1943, three Jews and the four Poles [[Rescue of Jews by Poles during the Holocaust|hiding them]] were shot and buried on the grounds of Sokołów Małopolski's elementary school.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Megargee |first1=Geoffrey |title=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |date=2012 |publisher=University of Indiana Press |location=Bloomington, Indiana |isbn=978-0-253-35599-7 |page=Volume II, 577–579}}</ref> The number of the few Jewish survivors is unknown.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.sokolow-mlp.pl/ Official town webpage]\n*[http://www.sokolow-mlp.go.pl/ Old Sokolow Malopolski photographs]; taken about 24 years ago.\n\n{{Commons category|Sokołów Małopolski}}\n\n{{Gmina Sokołów Małopolski}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Subcarpathian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Rzeszów County]]"
